\begin_layout Title
Midterm Microeconomics 2024
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Victor H.
 Aguiar 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
This version:
 November 2024
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(30 points) Consumer Theory with the Weak Axiom of Revealed Preference.
 WARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 be the standard commodity space with 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Define a preference function 
\begin_inset Formula $r:X\times X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 associated with a preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

,
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)>0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

).
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 may not be rational.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Consider the following particular model of consumer behavior.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{1,\cdots,J\}$
\end_inset

,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{j}$
\end_inset

 be a a finite collection of utilities such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 it's a utility function that is continuous,
 strictly monotone and concave.
 Now,
 consider a consumer that has the following preferences (multiple-utility–MU–model):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(x,y)=\max_{j\in\{1,\cdots,J\}}\min_{u\in U_{j}}(u(x)-u(y)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Intuitively,
 this MU model says that the consumer does not have a single utility to compare between any two consumption bundles,
 it may have many such utilities.
 In order to decide if she likes 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 better than 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 this consumer first picks the worst case over a particular criterion 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{j}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{u\in U_{j}}(u(x)-u(y))$
\end_inset

,
 and then if there is at least one criterion (some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

) for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{u\in U_{j}}(u(x)-u(y))\geq0$
\end_inset

 the comparison is favorable to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 then it will declare that 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 (i.e.,
 the max over 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the previous statement).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A\subseteq}2^{X}\setminus\emptyset$
\end_inset

 be a collection of menus/choice sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
We define a choice correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $c:\mathcal{A}\to2^{X}\setminus\emptyset$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $c(A)\subseteq A$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a choice correspondence admits a MU preference function rationalization if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c(A)=\{a\in A:r(a,b)\geq0\forall b\in A\},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a MU such that 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)=\max_{j\in\{1,\cdots,J\}}\min_{u\in U_{j}}(u(x)-u(y))$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq^{D}$
\end_inset

 be defined as the direct revealed preference such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{D}y\iff x\in c(A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in A$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ^{D}y\iff x\in c(A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in A$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin c(A)$
\end_inset

.
 We say WARP holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{D}y$
\end_inset

 implies not 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ^{D}x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 (10 points) Show that associated preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 to the MU preference function above may fail to be rational.
 Hint:
 Build a particular model that fails transitivity or completeness,
 that it's a MU preference function.
 You can simplify the problem assuming for this numeral only that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is finite and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 consists of tuples and triples 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y\},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y,z\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 (10 points) Show that when the multiple criteria are coherent,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{j}\cap U_{i}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

,
 then a choice correspondence that admits a MU preference function rationalization satisfies WARP.
 Namely,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{D}y$
\end_inset

 then it cannot be that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ^{D}x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 (10 points) Partial converse.
 Assume now that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is such that it contains every tuple and triple choice set such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y\},\{x,y,z\}\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Show that if a choice correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 defined on this collection of choice sets satisfies WARP then there is a MU preference function that rationalizes it.
 For this exercise you can assume that the preference relation that rationalizes this data set is a continuous preference relation and that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 (Hint:
 note that we are assuming that the choice correspondence it's nonempty).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Quasilinear Welfare Analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Consider a finite dataset of observations 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{T}=\{p^{t},x^{t}\}_{t=1}^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Consider a consumer that maximizes a quasilinear utility function,
 such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{t}\in arg\max_{x\in X}u(x)-p^{t}\cdot x,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
for a given price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{t}\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a continuous,
 concave,
 strictly increasing utility function,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
1) Show that the dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{T}$
\end_inset

 is such that there exists numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{t}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{\textbf{QuasilinearAfriat Inequalities}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v^{t}-v^{s}\geq p^{t}\cdot(x^{t}-x^{s})=p^{t}(x^{t}-x^{s})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t,s\in\{1,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset

 (Note:
 the dot product notation is omitted as indicated above).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
2) Show that we can bound below the utility difference between any two bundles 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t},x^{s}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{t})-u(x^{s})$
\end_inset

,
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x^{t})-u(x^{s})\geq p^{t}(x^{t}-x^{1})+p^{1}(x^{1}-x^{2})+\cdots+p^{n}(x^{n}-x^{s}),
\]

\end_inset

for any arbitrary subsequence of data points 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{i},x^{i})_{i=1}^{n}\subseteq O^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 (This is useful for welfare analysis).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
3) The indirect utility of a price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{t}$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(p^{t})=\max_{x}u(x)-p^{t}x.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s}x^{t}\geq(>)p^{t}x^{t}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p^{t})-v(p^{s})\geq(>)0.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
4) Show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{T}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Quasilinear Afriat Inequalities,
 there is a concave,
 strictly increasing continuous utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

,
 such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{t}\in arg\max_{x\in X}u(x)-p^{t}\cdot x,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\{1,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
5) Say that inflation rate is such that,
 and out-of-sample (not in 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{T})$
\end_inset

 price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{T+1}$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}(p^{2}-p^{1})\geq0,x^{2}(p^{3}-p^{2})\geq0,\cdots,x^{T}(p^{T+1}-p^{T})\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 What can I conclude in terms of welfare for this individual:
 Is she better-off or worse-off in 
\begin_inset Formula $T+1,$
\end_inset

 with respect to every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\{1,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset

?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(Attraction Effect and Choice Overload)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(60 points) (Too much choice/Choice overload and the Attraction Effect) Propose a model for consumer behavior that captures the following stylized facts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choice Overload:
 Consumers are more likely to choose an outside option (that we equate in this problem to not choosing) when the size of the menu is too big.
 Hint:
 The choice set is 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cup\{o\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $o$
\end_inset

 is an outside option (not in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be finite.
 Menus are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup\{o\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq X$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.,
 the outside option is always available to the consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Attraction Effect:The 
\series bold
attraction effect
\series default
 is the observation that if we add an alternative to a menu,
 then some existing item becomes more attractive to the consumer and is picked by her.
 This introduced object is usually called the decoy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In formal terms,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-}\in X$
\end_inset

 be the decoy,
 so we are going to study its impact in the choice of the object of interest 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in X$
\end_inset

.
 The observation is the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\in c(A\cup\{b^{-}\})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\notin c(A),b\in A.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In probabilities,
 it means that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(b,A\cup\{b^{-}\})>p(b,A).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You should describe with words what is the consumer choice algorithm.
 The model can be deterministic or stochastic,
 your choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then you should describe what is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in your model and how that relates to some behavioral or bounded rationality feature we learned in class,
 and how it differs from utility maximization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally you should write the behavioral maximization problem and show how your new model predicts the two stylized facts.
 Also show,
 that the rational benchmark cannot deal with this models (neither random utility or deterministic utility maximization can predict the choice overload or attraction effect).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You should try to explain the model to me in the best way you can,
 by using words,
 diagrams and examples.
 However,
 you should have also formality,
 make the effort to write down the model using math,
 this is the only way to get full credit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Describe what other testable implications your proposed model has.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Grading Criterion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Work group is not allowed,
 if I find out that several of you have essentially the same model,
 you will receive the total grade of this question divided by the number of students that share the same response.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The last question will be graded on the following 5 items:
 Logical consistency of the decision algorithm.
 Clarity of the explanation of the decision algorithm.
 Degree of success in explaining the behavioral effects.
 Clarity in the explanation of the behavioral effect using the decision algorithm.
 Ability of your model to be able to have testable implications (not everything goes).
 
\end_layout

